# Semantic HTML

**Whenever you generate or edit UI markup** (React/Next components, layouts, HTML fragments, MDX with structure), prefer **meaningful elements** over generic `div`/`span` wrappers.

## Structure and landmarks

- One **`main`** per page for primary content; use **`header`**, **`footer`**, **`nav`**, **`aside`**, **`section`**, **`article`** when they match the role of the block.
- Use **`h1`–`h6`** in order for headings; do not skip levels for styling—adjust styles with CSS/Tailwind instead.

## Interactive and form content

- **`button`** for actions (submit, open, toggle); use **`type="button"`** when not submitting a form. Use **`a href`** for navigation. Avoid `div`/`span` with `onClick` unless there is no semantic alternative and accessibility is fully handled.
- **`form`**, **`label`** (associated with controls via `htmlFor`/`id`), **`fieldset`**/**`legend`** for related groups when helpful.
- Native inputs: **`input`**, **`textarea`**, **`select`**, **`option`** with correct **`type`** and accessible names.

## Lists and text

- **`ul`**/**`ol`**/**`li`** for lists; **`dl`**/**`dt`**/**`dd`** for description lists when appropriate.
- **`p`** for paragraphs; **`strong`**/**`em`** for importance/emphasis, not only bold/italic styling. **`p`** must not wrap **block-level** children (e.g. `div`, another `p`, sectioning elements, cards that render `div`s)—use **`div`** with appropriate text styling if the child tree is unknown or includes blocks.

## Media and data

- **`img`** with meaningful **`alt`** (empty `alt=""` only when decorative); **`figure`**/**`figcaption`** when captioning.
- **`table`**/**`thead`**/**`tbody`**/**`tr`**/**`th`**/**`td`** for tabular data, not for arbitrary layout.

## Valid hierarchy (avoid hydration mismatches)

Browsers **repair invalid HTML** by moving or closing tags. **React compares the server HTML to the client tree**; if the live DOM differs, you get hydration errors or subtle bugs.

- **No interactive inside interactive**: do not nest **`button`** in **`button`**, **`a`** in **`a`**, or **`button`** inside **`a`** / **`a`** inside **`button`** (unless using a single delegated pattern documented by your UI kit).
- **Phrasing vs block**: do not put **`div`**, **`section`**, **`ul`**, **`h1`–`h6`**, or other **flow/block** elements inside **`p`**, **`span`**, **`label`** (when the label wraps complex layout), or **`a`** when it would break link phrasing content rules.
- **Lists**: **`li`** only under **`ul`**, **`ol`**, or **`menu`**; direct children of lists must be **`li`** (or script/template per spec).
- **Tables**: **`tr`** in **`thead`**/**`tbody`**/**`tfoot`**; **`th`**/**`td`** only in **`tr`**—no skipping structural wrappers for layout hacks.
- **Headings**: one logical outline; avoid duplicating **`h1`** in a way that splits landmarks incorrectly across server/client conditional branches.

Prefer **`Fragment`** or a **`div`** wrapper over forcing a **`p`** when composing **child components** that may render blocks. Let the repo’s ESLint setup (e.g. **jsx-a11y** and any DOM-nesting rules) catch invalid trees in CI.

## Accessibility tie-in

- Prefer semantics that convey role to assistive tech; add **`aria-*`** only when semantics are insufficient (e.g. composite widgets, live regions).
- Do not remove visible focus styles; visible focus and keyboard operability stay in line with semantic controls.

## Quick anti-patterns

```tsx
// ❌ BAD — div soup, fake button
<div className="cursor-pointer" onClick={onSubmit}>Send</div>

// ✅ GOOD
<button type="submit">Send</button>
```

```tsx
// ❌ BAD — heading for styling only
<h4 className="text-2xl font-bold">Page title</h4>

// ✅ GOOD — correct level for outline
<h1 className="text-2xl font-bold">Page title</h1>
```

```tsx
// ❌ BAD — <p> cannot contain <div>; browser closes <p> early → SSR/client mismatch
<p>
  <Card /> {/* renders a div */}
</p>

// ✅ GOOD
<div className="text-base text-muted-foreground">
  <Card />
</div>
```

When a **shadcn/ui** or design-system primitive renders a `div` for layout but exposes the right role (e.g. `Dialog`, `Tabs`), use that component’s documented patterns; still choose semantic structure **around** it (landmarks, headings, real buttons where the API allows).
